<dl id="n12166k"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12166k">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12166k"> 166(k)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> church all bishops</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">But whereas elsewhere it was the exception, in Ireland it seems to have become the rule. The desire of new foundations to be self-sufficient and completely independent of the diocesan bishop would not perhaps have been so strong if the diocesan bishop had not usually been associated with one of the older monasteries. But once the practice of bishops without sees was introduced, <mark>bishops multiplied like flies</mark>. A new and narrow conception of the episcopal office prevailed, and when it was recognised that bishops need not have sees, there was no reason to set a limit to their number. The order of bishop became a dignity to which any man of piety might aspire. <small> J.B. Bury, <a name="JBSP" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#JBSP"><cite title="source">Life of Saint Patrick</cite></a> (1905) 181</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c12167k" href="c12all.htm#c12167k">VI.C.12:167(k)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
